main event: On April 18, 1956, a UFO sighting was reported in the SE corner of Minnesota. The observation was made using ground radar for a duration of forty minutes. An object smaller than the planets, appearing to change colors, moved erratically before fading out of sight. It was not picked up on radar.
interesting points: The UFO moved erratically from side to side, suggesting unconventional flight patterns.
The sighting lasted for forty minutes, providing a relatively long observation period.
The object appeared smaller than the planets and changed colors, indicating a dynamic appearance.
No radar contact was made with the object, raising questions about its physical presence.
The conclusion pointed towards natural causes, such as movements of heavenly bodies or possibly a balloon or asteroid.
sighted object: Unidentified object resembling a point of light that changed colors
witnesses: Observation made by Airman Robert F. Hansen, commanding officer of the 44th Fighter Bomber Wing
photographs: No photographs included in the report
